```

In this program, the `longest_common_subsequence` function takes two strings `s1` and `s2` as input and returns their longest common subsequence. It uses a 2D array `m` to store the lengths of common subsequences ending at each position in `s1` and `s2`. The outer loop iterates over `s1`, the inner loop over `s2`. If the current characters in `s1` and `s2` are equal, the length of the common subsequence ending at this position is one more than the length ending at the previous position. If not, the length is the maximum of the lengths of the common subsequences ending at the previous positions without considering the current character of `s1` or `s2`. Finally, the function reconstructs the longest common subsequence from the bottom up by tracing back the positions in `m` where the characters were equal.

